TY  - JOUR
T1  - Industry Self-Regulation Without Sanctions: The Chemical Industry's Responsible Care Program
AU  - King, Andrew A.
AU  - Lenox, Michael J.
Y1  - 2000/08/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556362
DO  - 10.5465/1556362
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 698
EP  - 716
VL  - 43
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Industry self-regulation?the voluntary association of firms to control their collective action?has been proposed as a complement to government regulation. Proponents argue that the establishment of such structures may institutionalize environmental improvement, and critics suggest that without explicit sanctions, such structures will fall victim to opportunistic behavior. In a study of the Chemical Manufacturers Association's Responsible Care Program, we investigate the predictions of these two contradictory perspectives. Our findings highlight the potential for opportunism to overcome the isomorphic pressures of even powerful self-regulatory institutions and suggest that effective industry self-regulation is difficult to maintain without explicit sanctions.
AB  - Industry self-regulation?the voluntary association of firms to control their collective action?has been proposed as a complement to government regulation. Proponents argue that the establishment of such structures may institutionalize environmental improvement, and critics suggest that without explicit sanctions, such structures will fall victim to opportunistic behavior. In a study of the Chemical Manufacturers Association's Responsible Care Program, we investigate the predictions of these two contradictory perspectives. Our findings highlight the potential for opportunism to overcome the isomorphic pressures of even powerful self-regulatory institutions and suggest that effective industry self-regulation is difficult to maintain without explicit sanctions.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556362
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556362
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

